{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a477fbdb-a25d-47cd-91a9-28b6bd47806e","content":"Use conditional compilation or the `OnPlatform` pattern in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Each platform-specific class lives under `Platforms/<Platform>/` and implements `INotificationService`.\n- The `#if` directives ensure only the relevant implementation is compiled per target, so no missing-type errors at runtime.\n- Alternatively, you can avoid `#if` by using `Microsoft.Maui.Devices.DeviceInfo.Platform` at runtime, but conditional compilation is preferred since it excludes platform-specific APIs that won't exist on other targets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d469d1d6-d223-451c-99fc-6554eba12141","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection setup for platform-specific services. This is a general knowledge question about MAUI's `MauiProgram.cs` pattern — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"9BC4:11AB75:624A79B:6D88BCB:69EC1080"},"id":"479acef9-83e7-47a8-96bb-81a9229a92e0","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:53:28.382Z","parentId":"c8b892d5-2d99-444f-b0cd-97969c32c769"}
